# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: opentelemetry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:opentelemetry/cloud-native-computing-foundation] The **Cloud Native Computing Foundation** (**CNCF**) is a subsidiary of the Linux Foundation founded in 2015 to support cloud-native computing.
[src:opentelemetry/cloud-native-computing-foundation] It was announced alongside Kubernetes 1.0, an open source container cluster manager, which was contributed to the Linux Foundation by Google as a seed technology.
[src:opentelemetry/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Founding members include Google, CoreOS, Mesosphere, Red Hat, Twitter, Huawei, Intel, RX-M, Cisco, IBM, Docker, Univa, and VMware.
[src:opentelemetry/cloud-native-computing-foundation] Today, CNCF is supported by over 450 members.
[src:opentelemetry/cloud-native-computing-foundation] In August 2018 Google announced that it was handing over operational control of Kubernetes to the community.
[src:opentelemetry/concepts] This section covers data sources and key components of the OpenTelemetry project, which can help you understand how OpenTelemetry works.
[src:opentelemetry/concepts] Learn about the concept that enables Distributed Tracing.
[src:opentelemetry/concepts] Common names for different kinds of operations and data.
[src:opentelemetry/concepts] Learn about sampling and the different sampling options available in OpenTelemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/concepts] A distribution, not to be confused with a fork, is a customized version of an OpenTelemetry component.
[src:opentelemetry/concepts] Definitions and conventions for telemetry terms as used in OpenTelemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:opentelemetry/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:opentelemetry/page] OpenTelemetry, also known as OTel, is a vendor-neutral open source Observability framework for instrumenting, generating, collecting, and exporting telemetry data such as traces, metrics, and logs.
[src:opentelemetry/page] As an industry-standard, OpenTelemetry is supported by more than 90 observability vendors, integrated by many libraries, services, and apps, and adopted by numerous end users.
[src:opentelemetry/page] A brief explanation of what OpenTelemetry is and isn’t.
[src:opentelemetry/page] Get started with OpenTelemetry based on your role.
[src:opentelemetry/page] Vendor-agnostic way to receive, process and export telemetry data.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] The path of a request through your application.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] The following JSON examples do not represent a specific format, and especially not OTLP/JSON, which is more verbose.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] This is the root span, denoting the beginning and end of the entire operation.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Note that it has a `trace_id` field indicating the trace, but has no `parent_id`.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] This span encapsulates specific tasks, like saying greetings, and its parent is the `hello` span.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Note that it shares the same `trace_id` as the root span, indicating it’s a part of the same trace.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Additionally, it has a `parent_id` that matches the `span_id` of the `hello` span.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] This span represents the third operation in this trace and, like the previous one, it’s a child of the `hello` span.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] That also makes it a sibling of the `hello-greetings` span.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] These three blocks of JSON all share the same `trace_id`, and the `parent_id` field represents a hierarchy.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Another thing you’ll note is that each Span looks like a structured log.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] One way to think of Traces is that they’re a collection of structured logs with context, correlation, hierarchy, and more baked in.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] However, these “structured logs” can come from different processes, services, VMs, data centers, and so on.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] This is what allows tracing to represent an end-to-end view of any system.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] To understand how tracing in OpenTelemetry works, let’s look at a list of components that will play a part in instrumenting our code.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A Tracer Provider (sometimes called `TracerProvider`) is a factory for `Tracer`s.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] In most applications, a Tracer Provider is initialized once and its lifecycle matches the application’s lifecycle.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Tracer Provider initialization also includes Resource and Exporter initialization.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] It is typically the first step in tracing with OpenTelemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] In some language SDKs, a global Tracer Provider is already initialized for you.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A Tracer creates spans containing more information about what is happening for a given operation, such as a request in a service.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Tracers are created from Tracer Providers.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Trace Exporters send traces to a consumer.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] This consumer can be standard output for debugging and development-time, the OpenTelemetry Collector, or any open source or vendor backend of your choice.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Context Propagation is the core concept that enables Distributed Tracing.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] With Context Propagation, Spans can be correlated with each other and assembled into a trace, regardless of where Spans are generated.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] To learn more about this topic, see the concept page on Context Propagation.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A **span** represents a unit of work or operation.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Spans are the building blocks of Traces.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Spans can be nested, as is implied by the presence of a parent span ID: child spans represent sub-operations.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] This allows spans to more accurately capture the work done in an application.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Span context is the part of a span that is serialized and propagated alongside Distributed Context and Baggage.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Because Span Context contains the Trace ID, it is used when creating Span Links.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Attributes are key-value pairs that contain metadata that you can use to annotate a Span to carry information about the operation it is tracking.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] For example, if a span tracks an operation that adds an item to a user’s shopping cart in an eCommerce system, you can capture the user’s ID, the ID of the item to add to the cart, and the cart ID.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] You can add attributes to spans during or after span creation.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Prefer adding attributes at span creation to make the attributes available to SDK sampling.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] If you have to add a value after span creation, update the span with the value.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Additionally, there are Semantic Attributes, which are known naming conventions for metadata that is typically present in common operations.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] It’s helpful to use semantic attribute naming wherever possible so that common kinds of metadata are standardized across systems.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A Span Event can be thought of as a structured log message (or annotation) on a Span, typically used to denote a meaningful, singular point in time during the Span’s duration.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A Span is best used to track the first scenario because it’s an operation with a start and an end.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A Span Event is best used to track the second scenario because it represents a meaningful, singular point in time.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Since span events also contain attributes, the question of when to use events instead of attributes might not always have an obvious answer.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] To inform your decision, consider whether a specific timestamp is meaningful.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] For example, when you’re tracking an operation with a span and the operation completes, you might want to add data from the operation to your telemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Links exist so that you can associate one span with one or more spans, implying a causal relationship.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] For example, let’s say we have a distributed system where some operations are tracked by a trace.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] In response to some of these operations, an additional operation is queued to be executed, but its execution is asynchronous.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] We can track this subsequent operation with a trace as well.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] We would like to associate the trace for the subsequent operations with the first trace, but we cannot predict when the subsequent operations will start.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] We need to associate these two traces, so we will use a span link.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] You can link the last span from the first trace to the first span in the second trace.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Now, they are causally associated with one another.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Links are optional but serve as a good way to associate trace spans with one another.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A span status that is `Unset` means that the operation it tracked successfully completed without an error.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] When a span status is `Error`, then that means some error occurred in the operation it tracks.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] For example, this could be due to an HTTP 500 error on a server handling a request.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] When a span status is `Ok`, then that means the span was explicitly marked as error-free by the developer of an application.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Although this is unintuitive, it’s not required to set a span status as `Ok` when a span is known to have completed without error, as this is covered by `Unset`.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] What `Ok` does is represent an unambiguous “final call” on the status of a span that has been explicitly set by a user.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] This is helpful in any situation where a developer wishes for there to be no other interpretation of a span other than “successful”.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] To reiterate: `Unset` represents a span that completed without an error.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] `Ok` represents when a developer explicitly marks a span as successful.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] In most cases, it is not necessary to explicitly mark a span as `Ok`.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] When a span is created, it is one of `Client`, `Server`, `Internal`, `Producer`, or `Consumer`.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] This span kind provides a hint to the tracing backend as to how the trace should be assembled.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] According to the OpenTelemetry specification, the parent of a server span is often a remote client span, and the child of a client span is usually a server span.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Similarly, the parent of a consumer span is always a producer and the child of a producer span is always a consumer.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] If not provided, the span kind is assumed to be internal.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] For more information regarding SpanKind, see SpanKind.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A client span represents a synchronous outgoing remote call such as an outgoing HTTP request or database call.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Note that in this context, “synchronous” does not refer to `async/await`, but to the fact that it is not queued for later processing.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] A server span represents a synchronous incoming remote call such as an incoming HTTP request or remote procedure call.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Internal spans represent operations which do not cross a process boundary.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Things like instrumenting a function call or an Express middleware may use internal spans.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Producer spans represent the creation of a job which may be asynchronously processed later.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] It may be a remote job such as one inserted into a job queue or a local job handled by an event listener.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] Consumer spans represent the processing of a job created by a producer and may start long after the producer span has already ended.
[src:opentelemetry/signals-traces] For more information, see the traces specification.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Although the term commonly refers to wireless data transfer mechanisms (e.g., using radio, ultrasonic, or infrared systems), it also encompasses data transferred over other media such as a telephone or computer network, optical link or other wired communications like power line carriers.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Many modern telemetry systems take advantage of the low cost and ubiquity of GSM networks by using SMS to receive and transmit telemetry data.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] A *telemeter* is a physical device used in telemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] It consists of a sensor, a transmission path, and a display, recording, or control device.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Electronic devices are widely used in telemetry and can be wireless or hard-wired, analog or digital.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Other technologies are also possible, such as mechanical, hydraulic and optical.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry may be commutated to allow the transmission of multiple data streams in a fixed frame.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The beginning of industrial telemetry lies in the steam age, although the sensor was not called *telemeter* at that time.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Examples are James Watt's (1736-1819) additions to his steam engines for monitoring from a (near) distance such as the mercury pressure gauge and the fly-ball governor.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In 1889 this led an author in the Institution of Civil Engineers proceedings to suggest that the term for the rangefinder telemeter might be replaced with tacheometer.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In the 1930s use of electrical telemeters grew rapidly.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The electrical strain gauge was widely used in rocket and aviation research and the radiosonde was invented for meteorological measurements.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The advent of World War II gave an impetus to industrial development and henceforth many of these telemeters became commercially viable.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Carrying on from rocket research, radio telemetry was used routinely as space exploration got underway.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Spacecraft are in a place where a physical connection is not possible, leaving radio or other electromagnetic waves (such as infrared lasers) as the only viable option for telemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] During crewed space missions it is used to monitor not only parameters of the vehicle, but also the health and life support of the astronauts.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] During the Cold War telemetry found uses in espionage.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] US intelligence found that they could monitor the telemetry from Soviet missile tests by building a telemeter of their own to intercept the radio signals and hence learn a great deal about Soviet capabilities.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemeters are the physical devices used in telemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetering information over wire had its origins in the 19th century.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] One of the first data-transmission circuits was developed in 1845 between the Russian Tsar's Winter Palace and army headquarters.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In 1874, French engineers built a system of weather and snow-depth sensors on Mont Blanc that transmitted real-time information to Paris.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Michalke patented the selsyn, a circuit for sending synchronized rotation information over a distance.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In 1906 a set of seismic stations were built with telemetering to the Pulkovo Observatory in Russia.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In 1912, Commonwealth Edison developed a system of telemetry to monitor electrical loads on its power grid.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The Panama Canal (completed 1913–1914) used extensive telemetry systems to monitor locks and water levels.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Wireless telemetry made early appearances in the radiosonde, developed concurrently in 1930 by Robert Bureau in France and Pavel Molchanov in Russia.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Molchanov's system modulated temperature and pressure measurements by converting them to wireless Morse code.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The German V-2 rocket used a system of primitive multiplexed radio signals called "Messina" to report four rocket parameters, but it was so unreliable that Wernher von Braun once claimed it was more useful to watch the rocket through binoculars.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In the US and the USSR, the Messina system was quickly replaced with better systems; in both cases, based on pulse-position modulation (PPM).
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Early Soviet missile and space telemetry systems which were developed in the late 1940s used either PPM (e.g., the Tral telemetry system developed by OKB-MEI) or pulse-duration modulation (e.g., the RTS-5 system developed by NII-885).
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In the United States, early work employed similar systems, but were later replaced by pulse-code modulation (PCM) (for example, in the Mars probe Mariner 4).
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Later Soviet interplanetary probes used redundant radio systems, transmitting telemetry by PCM on a decimeter band and PPM on a centimeter band.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Although the two terms are closely related, telemetry and telematics are used differently depending on the field.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telematics, by contrast, emerged later as a broader, more applied concept that combines telemetry with telecommunications, informatics, and digital fleet platforms.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In short, telemetry is the enabling technology (remote measurement and data transmission), while telematics describes the integrated, digitalized applications that build on telemetry to deliver business, safety, and operational insights.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Weather balloons use telemetry to transmit meteorological data since 1920.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used to transmit drilling mechanics and formation evaluation information uphole, in real time, as a well is drilled.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] These services are known as Measurement while drilling and Logging while drilling.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Information acquired thousands of feet below ground, while drilling, is sent through the drilling hole to the surface sensors and the demodulation software.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The pressure wave (sana) is translated into useful information after DSP and noise filters.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] This information is used for Formation evaluation, Drilling Optimization, and Geosteering.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in modern motor racing, allowing race engineers to interpret data collected during a test or race and use it to properly tune the car for optimum performance.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Systems used in series such as Formula One have become advanced to the point where the potential lap time of the car can be calculated, and this time is what the driver is expected to meet.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Examples of measurements on a race car include accelerations (G forces) in three axes, temperature readings, wheel speed, and suspension displacement.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In Formula One, driver input is also recorded so the team can assess driver performance and (in case of an accident) the FIA can determine or rule out driver error as a possible cause.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Later developments include two-way telemetry which allows engineers to update calibrations on the car in real time (even while it is out on the track).
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In Formula One, two-way telemetry surfaced in the early 1990s and consisted of a message display on the dashboard which the team could update.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Its development continued until May 2001, when it was first allowed on the cars.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] By 2002, teams were able to change engine mapping and deactivate engine sensors from the pit while the car was on the track.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] For the 2003 season, the FIA banned two-way telemetry from Formula One; however, the technology may be used in other types of racing or on road cars.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] One way telemetry system has also been applied in R/C racing car to get information by car's sensors like: engine RPM, voltage, temperatures, throttle.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In the transportation industry, a Fleet telematics system is used to provide information about a vehicle or driver's performance by collecting data from on-board sensors, such as a GPS tracking unit or a telematics control unit (TCU).
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] This is undertaken for various reasons ranging from staff compliance monitoring, insurance rating, fuel management to predictive maintenance.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] As part of an Intelligent transportation system, telemetry is used to link traffic counter devices to data recorders to measure traffic flows and vehicle lengths and weights.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used by the railway industry for measuring the health of trackage.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] This permits optimized and focused predictive and preventative maintenance.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Typically this is done with specialized trains, such as the New Measurement Train used in the United Kingdom by Network Rail, which can check for track defects, such as problems with gauge, and deformations in the rail.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Japan uses similar, but quicker trains, nicknamed Doctor Yellow.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Such trains, besides checking the tracks, can also verify whether or not there are any problems with the overhead power supply (catenary), where it is installed.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Dedicated rail inspection companies, such as Sperry Rail, have their own customized rail cars and rail-wheel equipped trucks, that use a variety of methods, including lasers, ultrasound, and induction (measuring resulting magnetic fields from running electricity into rails) to find any defects.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Most activities related to healthy crops and good yields depend on timely availability of weather and soil data.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Therefore, wireless weather stations play a major role in disease prevention and precision irrigation.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Because local micro-climates can vary significantly, such data needs to come from within the crop.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Monitoring stations usually transmit data back by terrestrial radio, although occasionally satellite systems are used.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Solar power is often employed to make the station independent of the power grid.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in water management, including water quality and stream gauging functions.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Major applications include AMR (automatic meter reading), groundwater monitoring, leak detection in distribution pipelines and equipment surveillance.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Having data available in almost real time allows quick reactions to events in the field.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry control allows engineers to intervene with assets such as pumps and by remotely switching pumps on or off depending on the circumstances.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in complex systems such as missiles, RPVs, spacecraft, oil rigs, and chemical plants since it allows the automatic monitoring, alerting, and record-keeping necessary for efficient and safe operation.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Space agencies such as NASA, ISRO, the European Space Agency (ESA), and other agencies use telemetry and/or telecommand systems to collect data from spacecraft and satellites.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in the development of missiles, satellites and aircraft because the system might be destroyed during or after the test.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Engineers need critical system parameters to analyze (and improve) the performance of the system.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In the absence of telemetry, this data would often be unavailable.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used by crewed or uncrewed spacecraft for data transmission.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Distances of more than 25.1 billion kilometers (May 2025) have been covered, e.g., by Voyager 1.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In rocketry, telemetry equipment forms an integral part of the rocket range assets used to monitor the position and health of a launch vehicle to determine range safety flight termination criteria (Range purpose is for public safety).
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Problems include the extreme environment (temperature, acceleration and vibration), the energy supply, antenna alignment and (at long distances, e.g., in spaceflight) signal travel time.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Today nearly every type of aircraft, missiles, or spacecraft carries a wireless telemetry system as it is tested.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Aeronautical mobile telemetry is used for the safety of the pilots and persons on the ground during flight tests.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry from an on-board flight test instrumentation system is the primary source of real-time measurement and status information transmitted during the testing of crewed and uncrewed aircraft.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Intercepted telemetry was an important source of intelligence for the United States and UK when Soviet missiles were tested; for this purpose, the United States operated a listening post in Iran.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Eventually, the Russians discovered the United States intelligence-gathering network and encrypted their missile-test telemetry signals.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry was also a source for the Soviets, who operated listening ships in Cardigan Bay to eavesdrop on UK missile tests performed in the area.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In factories, buildings and houses, energy consumption of systems such as HVAC are monitored at multiple locations; related parameters (e.g., temperature) are sent via wireless telemetry to a central location.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The information is collected and processed, enabling the most efficient use of energy.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Such systems also facilitate predictive maintenance.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Many resources need to be distributed over wide areas.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is useful in these cases, since it allows the logistics system to channel resources where they are needed, as well as provide security for those assets; principal examples of this are dry goods, fluids, and granular bulk solids.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] This facilitates knowledge of their location, and can record their status and disposition, as when merchandise with barcode labels is scanned through a checkout reader at point-of-sale systems in a retail store.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Stationary or hand-held barcode RFID scanners or Optical reader with remote communications, can be used to expedite inventory tracking and counting in stores, warehouses, shipping terminals, transportation carriers and factories.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Fluids stored in tanks are a principal object of constant commercial telemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used to communicate the variable measurements of flow and tank level sensors detecting fluid movements and/or volumes by pneumatic, hydrostatic, or differential pressure; tank-confined ultrasonic, radar or Doppler effect echoes; or mechanical or magnetic sensors.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry of bulk solids is common for tracking and reporting the volume status and condition of grain and livestock feed bins, powdered or granular food, powders and pellets for manufacturing, sand and gravel, and other granular bulk solids.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] While technology associated with fluid tank monitoring also applies, in part, to granular bulk solids, reporting of overall container weight, or other gross characteristics and conditions, are sometimes required, owing to bulk solids' more complex and variable physical characteristics.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used for patients (biotelemetry) who are at risk of abnormal heart activity, generally in a coronary care unit.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry specialists are sometimes used to monitor many patients within a hospital.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Such patients are outfitted with measuring, recording and transmitting devices.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] A data log can be useful in diagnosis of the patient's condition by doctors.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] An alerting function can alert nurses if the patient is suffering from an acute (or dangerous) condition.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Systems are available in medical-surgical nursing for monitoring to rule out a heart condition, or to monitor a response to antiarrhythmic medications such as amiodarone.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] A new and emerging application for telemetry is in the field of neurophysiology, or neurotelemetry.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Neurophysiology is the study of the central and peripheral nervous systems through the recording of bioelectrical activity, whether spontaneous or stimulated.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In neurotelemetry (NT) the electroencephalogram (EEG) of a patient is monitored remotely by a registered EEG technologist using advanced communication software.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The goal of neurotelemetry is to recognize a decline in a patient's condition before physical signs and symptoms are present.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Neurotelemetry is synonymous with real-time continuous video EEG monitoring and has application in the epilepsy monitoring unit, neuro ICU, pediatric ICU and newborn ICU.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Due to the labor-intensive nature of continuous EEG monitoring NT is typically done in the larger academic teaching hospitals using in-house programs that include R.EEG Technologists, IT support staff, neurologist and neurophysiologist and monitoring support personnel.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Modern microprocessor speeds, software algorithms and video data compression allow hospitals to centrally record and monitor continuous digital EEGs of multiple critically ill patients simultaneously.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Neurotelemetry and continuous EEG monitoring provides dynamic information about brain function that permits early detection of changes in neurologic status, which is especially useful when the clinical examination is limited.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used to study wildlife, and has been useful for monitoring threatened species at the individual level.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Animals under study can be outfitted with instrumentation tags, which include sensors that measure temperature, diving depth and duration (for marine animals), speed and location (using GPS or Argos packages).
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry tags can give researchers information about animal behavior, functions, and their environment.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] This information is then either stored (with archival tags) or the tags can send (or transmit) their information to a satellite or handheld receiving device.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Capturing and marking wild animals can put them at some risk, so it is important to minimize these impacts.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] At a 2005 workshop in Las Vegas, a seminar noted the introduction of telemetry equipment which would allow vending machines to communicate sales and inventory data to a route truck or to a headquarters.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] This data could be used for a variety of purposes, such as eliminating the need for drivers to make a first trip to see which items needed to be restocked before delivering the inventory.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Retailers also use RFID tags to track inventory and prevent shoplifting.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Most of these tags passively respond to RFID readers (e.g., at the cashier), but active RFID tags are available which periodically transmit location information to a base station.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] A telemetry-based Tracking system is useful for tracking persons and property in law enforcement.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] An ankle collar worn by convicts on probation can warn authorities if a person violates the terms of his or her parole, such as by straying from authorized boundaries or visiting an unauthorized location.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry has also enabled bait cars, where law enforcement can rig a car with cameras and tracking equipment and leave it somewhere they expect it to be stolen.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] When stolen the telemetry equipment reports the location of the vehicle, enabling a Stolen vehicle recovery process where law enforcement can deactivate the engine and lock the doors when it is stopped by responding officers.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In some countries, telemetry is used to measure the amount of electrical energy consumed.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The electricity meter communicates with a concentrator, and the latter sends the information through GPRS or GSM to the energy provider's server.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is also used for the remote monitoring of substations and their equipment.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] For data transmission, phase line carrier systems operating on frequencies between 30 and 400 kHz are sometimes used.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In falconry, "telemetry" means a small radio transmitter carried by a bird of prey that will allow the bird's owner to track it when it is out of sight.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in testing hostile environments which are dangerous to humans.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Examples include munitions storage facilities, radioactive sites, volcanoes, deep sea, and outer space.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Telemetry is used in many battery operated wireless systems to inform monitoring personnel when the battery power is reaching a low point and the end item needs fresh batteries.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In the mining industry, telemetry serves two main purposes: the measurement of key parameters from mining equipment and the monitoring of safety practices.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] The information provided by the collection and analysis of key parameters allows for root-cause identification of inefficient operations, unsafe practices and incorrect equipment usage for maximizing productivity and safety.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Further applications of the technology allow for sharing knowledge and best practices across the organization.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In software, telemetry is used to gather data on the use and performance of applications and application components, e.g. how often certain features are used, measurements of start-up time and processing time, hardware, application crashes, and general usage statistics and/or user behavior.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] In some cases, very detailed data is reported like individual window metrics, counts of used features, and individual function timings.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] This kind of telemetry can be useful to software developers to receive data from a wide variety of endpoints that can't possibly all be tested in-house, as well as getting data on the popularity of certain features and whether they should be given priority or be considered for removal.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] Due to concerns about privacy since software telemetry can easily be used to profile users, telemetry in user software is often user choice, commonly presented as an opt-out feature (requiring explicit user action to disable it) or user choice during the software installation process.
[src:opentelemetry/telemetry] As in other telecommunications fields, international standards exist for telemetry equipment and software.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Logs that record program usage (such as a server log) or operating-system events primarily of interest to a system administrator (see for example *Event Viewer*) fall into a terminological gray area.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Tracing is primarily used for anomaly detection, fault analysis, debugging or diagnostic purposes in distributed software systems, such as microservices or serverless functions.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Software tracing is a tool for developers to gather information for debugging.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] This information is used both during development cycles and post-release.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Unlike event logging, software tracing usually does not have the concept of a "class" of event or an "event code".
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] OpenTelemetry is a CNCF open source project that provides comprehensive support for distributed tracing.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Some vendors including Datadog, Dynatrace, New Relic, Splunk also offer tracing SaaS services.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Google and Meta have developed their own tracing frameworks, named Dapper and Canopy respectively.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] In operating systems, tracing can be used in situations (such as booting) where some of the technologies used to provide event logging may not be available.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Linux offers system-level and user-level tracing capabilities with kernel markers and LTTng. ftrace also supports Linux kernel tracing. syslog is another tool in various operating systems for logging and tracing system messages.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] FreeBSD and SmartOS employ DTrace for tracing in both user space and kernel space.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] In embedded software, tracing also requires special techniques for efficient instrumentation and logging and low CPU overhead.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Trace generation of method calls can be done with source code instrumentation, runtime information collection, or under debugger control.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Tracing macros, aspect-oriented programming and related instrumentation techniques can be employed.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Libraries used in source code send data to an agent or directly to the collection component.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] To model execution trees, ISVis converts a rooted tree into a directed acyclic graph while Jinsight utilizes the call frame principle to gather and represent cumulative information about traces.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] The primary visualization method is the swimlane view, which is exemplified by tools like Jaeger and often includes annotations and key-value attributes.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Despite its widespread use, this design lacks rigorous justification and users frequently face challenges like missing features and confusing navigation.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Alternatives to swimlane views exist, like Jaeger’s service dependency view or SkyWalking’s List, Tree, and Table views.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Aggregate visualizations are also used for analyzing large volumes of traces, with systems like Canopy offering queryable metrics and Jaeger providing trace comparison features.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Event logging provides system administrators with information useful for diagnostics and auditing.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] The different classes of events that will be logged, as well as what details will appear in the event messages, are often considered early in the development cycle.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Many event logging technologies allow or even require each class of event to be assigned a unique "code", which is used by the event logging software or a separate viewer (e.g., Event Viewer) to format and output a human-readable message.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] This facilitates localization and allows system administrators to more easily obtain information on problems that occur.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Because event logging is used to log high-level information (often failure information), performance of the logging implementation is often less important.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] A special concern, preventing duplicate events from being recorded "too often" is taken care of through event throttling.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Difficulties in making a clear distinction between event logging and software tracing arise from the fact that some of the same technologies are used for both, and further because many of the criteria that distinguish between the two are continuous rather than discrete.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Enabling or disabling tracing during runtime often necessitates the inclusion of extra data in the binary.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] This can lead to performance degradation, even when tracing is not active.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] The overhead of tracing depends on the used framework and the activated features; in production servers, there is a trade-off between how fine-grained the tracing is and the incurred overhead.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] If tracing is enabled or disabled at compile-time, collecting trace data from a client's system hinges on their willingness and capability to install a version of the software specifically enabled for tracing, and subsequently replicate the issue.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Tracing in software typically demands high standards of robustness, not only in the accuracy and reliability of the trace output but also in ensuring that the process being traced remains uninterrupted.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] Given its low-level nature, tracing can generate a large volume of messages.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] To mitigate performance issues, it's often necessary to have the option to deactivate software tracing, either at the time of compilation or during run-time.
[src:opentelemetry/tracing-software] In proprietary software, tracing data may include sensitive information about the product's source code.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] A major goal of OpenTelemetry is to enable easy instrumentation of your applications and systems, regardless of the programming language, infrastructure, and runtime environments used.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] The backend (storage) and the frontend (visualization) of telemetry data are intentionally left to other tools.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] For more videos in this series and additional resources, see What next?
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] Observability is the ability to understand the internal state of a system by examining its outputs.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] In software, this is typically achieved by analyzing telemetry data such as traces, metrics, and logs.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] To make a system observable, it must be instrumented.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] That is, the code must emit traces, metrics, or logs.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] The instrumented data must then be sent to an observability backend.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] With the rise of cloud computing, microservices architectures, and increasingly complex business requirements, the need for software and infrastructure observability is greater than ever.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] You only have to learn a single set of APIs and conventions.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] Both principles combined grant teams and organizations the flexibility they need in today’s modern computing world.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] If you want to learn more, take a look at OpenTelemetry’s mission, vision, and values.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] OpenTelemetry is used by a wide variety of libraries, services and apps that have OpenTelemetry integrated to provide observability by default.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] OpenTelemetry is supported by numerous vendors, many of whom provide commercial support for OpenTelemetry and contribute to the project directly.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] OpenTelemetry is designed to be extensible.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] Although most users might not need to extend OpenTelemetry, the project is designed to make it possible at nearly every level.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] OpenTelemetry is a Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) project that is the result of a merger between two prior projects, OpenTracing and OpenCensus.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] Both of these projects were created to solve the same problem: the lack of a standard for how to instrument code and send telemetry data to an Observability backend.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] As neither project was fully able to solve the problem independently, they merged to form OpenTelemetry and combine their strengths while offering a single solution.
[src:opentelemetry/what-is-opentelemetry] If you are currently using OpenTracing or OpenCensus, you can learn how to migrate to OpenTelemetry in the Migration guide.
